steps_taken.description: LLM synthesis of all research findings

key_findings: Bug-type Pokémon are weak to Flying, Rock, and Fire types.
Key Bug-type Pokémon available from Generation I include Caterpie, Butterfree, Beedrill, Scyther, and Pinsir.
Certain Bug-type Pokémon such as Butterfree can learn supportive moves like Tackle, providing additional strategic utility in battle.
Common abilities of Bug-type Pokémon like Swarm can enhance Bug-type moves when HP is low, offering tactical advantages.
outputs.comprehensive_conclusion: Building a Bug-type Pokémon team requires careful consideration of their weaknesses and move sets to effectively counter opposing types. Selecting a diverse range of Bug Pokémon from different generations, such as Scyther with its high attack stats and Butterfree for its versatility, ensures broad strategic coverage. Leveraging abilities such as Swarm and moves like Silver Wind can bolster the team's effectiveness, compensating for inherent weaknesses.
actionable_recommendations: Incorporate a mix of defensive and offensive Bug-type Pokémon to balance the team’s capabilities.
Strategically use item enhancements such as Focus Sash on lead Pokémon like Scyther to survive unexpected strong attacks.
Deploy Pokémon with Flying or Psychic moves, such as Butterfree’s Psychic, to cover Bug-type vulnerabilities.
outputs.evidence_summary: The research was compiled using endpoints focused on Pokémon types, abilities, and moves. Key Pokémon and their abilities were identified, demonstrating their strategic potential in an all Bug-type team.
advantages_over_simple_llm: Direct API data utilization allows precise retrieval of specific Pokémon characteristics including types, abilities, and compatible moves, which are not subject to hallucination as can happen with a pure LLM approach.
The research strategy applies a systematic examination of endpoints to ensure all relevant aspects of team building are covered, from type effectiveness to move compatibility.
outputs.research_quality_assessment: The research is thorough, covering the necessary aspects of building a specialized Pokémon team. The systematic use of endpoint data delivers precise identification of potential team members, taking team weaknesses and strengths into account.
outputs.data_limitations: The compressed dataset restricts the availability of data across all generations, focusing primarily on early generation Pokémon. Additionally, move diversity and up-to-date team strategies beyond the included datasets weren't available.

effect_entries.effect: Verhindert keine regulären K.O. bei vollen hp.
Does not prevent regular KOs from full HP.

Wenn das Pokémon volle hp hat, lässt jeder Treffer der das Pokémon besiegt hätte ein hp übrig. Das Pokémon ist immun gegen die K.O.-Attacken fissure, guillotine, horn drill und sheer cold.

Hält das Pokémon ein focus sash, hat die Fähigkeit Vorrang und das Item wird nicht verbraucht.
effect_entries.short_effect: Verhindert K.O.-Treffer bei vollen hp, das Pokémon behält 1 hp. Schützt gegen K.O.-Attacken.

effect_entries.effect:
When this Pokémon is at full HP, any hit that would knock it out will instead leave it with 1 HP.  Regardless of its current HP, it is also immune to the one-hit KO moves: fissure, guillotine, horn drill, and sheer cold.

If this Pokémon is holding a focus sash, this ability takes precedence and the item will not be consumed.
effect_entries.short_effect: Prevents being KOed from full HP, leaving 1 HP instead.  Protects against the one-hit KO moves regardless of HP.

Hat keinen Effekt, wenn die Fähigkeit nach Kampfbeginn erlangt wurde.
Does not take effect if acquired after entering battle.

Wenn ein Pokémon mit dieser Fähigkeit den Kampf betritt, wird der attack des Gegners um 1 Stufe gesenkt. Im Mehrfachkämpfen werden alle Gegner beeinflusst.

Diese Fähigkeit löst auch aus, wenn sie im Kampf erlangt wurde, aber nicht, wenn sie verloren und zurückerlangt wurde.

Die Fähigkeit hat keinen Einfluss auf Gegner mit einem substitute.

Außerhalb vom Kampf: Wenn das erste Pokémon im Team diese Fähigkeit hat, dann hat jede Begegnung mit einem Pokémon das 5 oder mehr Level niedriger ist, eine Chance von 50% übersprungen zu werden.

effect_entries.effect:
When this Pokémon enters battle, the opponent's Attack is lowered by one stage.  In a double battle, both opponents are affected.

This ability also takes effect when acquired during a battle, but will not take effect again if lost and reobtained without leaving battle.

This ability has no effect on an opponent that has a substitute.

Overworld: If the first Pokémon in the party has this ability, any random encounter with a Pokémon five or more levels lower than it has a 50% chance of being skipped.

key_findings: Bug-type Pokémon are weak to Flying, Rock, and Fire types.
Key Bug-type Pokémon available from Generation I include Caterpie, Butterfree, Beedrill, Scyther, and Pinsir.
Certain Bug-type Pokémon such as Butterfree can learn supportive moves like Tackle, providing additional strategic utility in battle.
Common abilities of Bug-type Pokémon like Swarm can enhance Bug-type moves when HP is low, offering tactical advantages.
conclusion: Building a Bug-type Pokémon team requires careful consideration of their weaknesses and move sets to effectively counter opposing types. Selecting a diverse range of Bug Pokémon from different generations, such as Scyther with its high attack stats and Butterfree for its versatility, ensures broad strategic coverage. Leveraging abilities such as Swarm and moves like Silver Wind can bolster the team's effectiveness, compensating for inherent weaknesses.
recommendations: Incorporate a mix of defensive and offensive Bug-type Pokémon to balance the team’s capabilities.
Strategically use item enhancements such as Focus Sash on lead Pokémon like Scyther to survive unexpected strong attacks.
Deploy Pokémon with Flying or Psychic moves, such as Butterfree’s Psychic, to cover Bug-type vulnerabilities.
advantages_over_simple_llm: Direct API data utilization allows precise retrieval of specific Pokémon characteristics including types, abilities, and compatible moves, which are not subject to hallucination as can happen with a pure LLM approach.
The research strategy applies a systematic examination of endpoints to ensure all relevant aspects of team building are covered, from type effectiveness to move compatibility.
